  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing them through a series of transactions or financial systems. The purpose is to disguise the origin of the money so it can be used without detection of its illicit source.\n\n### Key Aspects of Money Laundering:\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal proceeds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the economy as legitimate funds.\n\n### Legal Consequences:\n- **Criminal Charges**: Money laundering is a serious crime that can result in significant penalties, including imprisonment, fines, or both.\n- **Civil Penalties**: Authorities may seize assets linked to money laundering operations.\n- **International Agreements**: Many countries cooperate under frameworks like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** to combat money laundering globally.\n\nIf someone is caught laundering money, they can face prosecution under both domestic and international laws, depending on the jurisdiction and the scale of the operation.",
